The only production for the start symbol is  

 S → NT23 NT34  

and the only production for NT34 is  

 NT34 → NT169 NT84  

The only production for NT84 is  

 NT84 → NT199 NT82  

Therefore every derivation from S must contain the non–terminal NT199.  
However, the grammar gives no rule of the form  

 NT199 → …  

(or NT199 → terminal) – NT199 is never defined.  
Since an undefined non-terminal cannot yield any terminal string, NT84, NT34 and consequently S are incapable of producing any string of terminals at all.  

Hence the provided string cannot be generated by this grammar.  

No

The start symbol S can only expand as

S → NT23 NT34

Hence the generated string must begin with a block produced by NT23.

All possibilities for NT23 are:

1. NT23 → NT118 NT20  
   NT118 → ‘t14’              ⇒ sequence “t14 t4”  
   NT118 → NT14 NT15  
        NT14 → ‘t26’ or ‘t17’  
        NT15 → ‘t10’          ⇒ sequences “t26 t10 t4” or “t17 t10 t4”

2. NT23 → NT197 NT196  
   NT197 → NT85 NT145  
        NT85 → ‘t22’ or ‘t27’  
        NT145 → NT74 NT180  
              NT74 → ‘t0’  
              NT180 → NT99 NT46  
                   NT99 → ‘t13’ (shortest form)  
                   NT46 → ‘t10’  
        ⇒ sequences “t22 t0 t13 t10 t14” or “t27 t0 t13 t10 t14”
   NT196 → ‘t14’

Therefore every string derived from NT23 must start with one of the following prefixes:

t14 t4  
t26 t10 t4  
t17 t10 t4  
t22 t0 …  
t27 t0 …

The string to be checked starts with

t27 t19 …

Since none of the allowable NT23 prefixes begins t27 t19, the first block required by S cannot match the given string. Consequently no derivation from S can yield the entire string.

Therefore the grammar does not generate the provided string.

No
